&lt;span class="wl-item"&gt;&lt;span class="wl-dot" style="background:var(--u2)"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;U2 ~11%&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="wl-item"&gt;&lt;span class="wl-dot" style="background:var(--u3)"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;U3 ~11%&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="wl-item"&gt;&lt;span class="wl-dot" style="background:var(--u4)"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;U4 ~14%&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="wl-item"&gt;&lt;span class="wl-dot" style="background:var(--u5)"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;U5 ~14%&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="wl-item"&gt;&lt;span class="wl-dot" style="background:var(--u6)"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;U6 ~14%&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="wl-item"&gt;&lt;span class="wl-dot" style="background:var(--u7)"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;U7 ~11%&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;!-- ═══════════════════════════════ SECTION I ═══════════════════════════════ --&gt;
&lt;div class="sec-head"&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;Section I — Multiple Choice&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;div class="sec-meta"&gt;60 Questions · 60 Minutes&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="directions"&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Directions:&lt;/strong&gt; Select the single best answer for each question. No penalty for wrong answers. Stimulus-based questions include a map, table, or scenario. Note: answer choices are deliberately similar in length — select based on geographic reasoning, not length.
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div id="mcq-wrap"&gt;
&lt;!-- Q1 U1 1A --&gt;
&lt;div class="mcq" id="q1" data-ans="B"&gt;
&lt;div class="q-row"&gt;&lt;span class="q-num"&gt;Q1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;div class="tags"&gt;&lt;span class="tag u1"&gt;Unit 1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="tag sk"&gt;Skill 1A&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p class="stem"&gt;An isoline map of annual precipitation across South Asia uses lines connecting points of equal rainfall. A geographer wants to add a second variable — population density — to the same map. Which of the following best explains why overlaying a choropleth layer on an isoline map can cause misinterpretation?&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>